itius]]\n\n==References and Notes==\n;References\n{{reflist|30em}}\n;Notes\n{{Reflist|30em|group=\"Note\"}}\n\n{{Foreign relations of Mauritius}}\n{{Visa Requirements}}\n{{Visa policy by country}}\n\n[[Category:Visa requirements by nationality|Mauritius]]\n[[Category:Foreign relations of Mauritius]]\n", "name_user": "Valpainit", "label": "safe", "comment": "Update Henley Index information", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Visa_requirements_for_Mauritian_citizens"}
{"title_page": "Peter Allan (priest)", "text_new": "{{short description|British Anglican priest and monk|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Infobox Christian leader\n| type             = Priest\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Reverend]] Fr\n| name             = Peter Allan\n| honorific-suffix = [[Community of the Resurrection|CR]]\n| title            = [[Principal (academia)|Principal]] of the [[College of the Resurrection]]\n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| church           = [[Church of England]]\n| province         = \n| diocese          = [[Anglican Diocese of Leeds|Leeds]]\n| term             = 2011\u20132019\n| predecessor      = [[Joseph Kennedy (priest)|Joseph Kennedy]]\n| successor        = [[Mark Sowerby]]\n| other_post       = Monk of the [[Community of the Resurrection]] (1985\u2013present)\n<!---------- Orders ---------->\n| ordination       = 1975 (deacon) <br /> 1976 (priest)\n| ordained_by      = \n| consecration     = \n| consecrated_by   = \n<!---------- Personal details ---------->\n| birth_name       = \n| birth_date       = {{birth year and age|1950}} <!-- {{Birth date|df=y|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| birth_place      = <!-- City, administrative region, sovereign state (per [[Template:Infobox person]]) -->\n| death_date       = <!-- {{Death date and age|df=y|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place      = <!-- as birth_place -->\n| buried           = <!-- or | tomb = -->\n| resting_place_co-ordinates = \n| nationality      = British\n| religion         = [[Anglicanism]]\n| residence        = \n| parents          = \n| spouse           = \n| children         = \n| occupation       = \n| profession       = <!-- or | previous_post = -->\n| education        =\n| alma_mater       = [[Wadham College, Oxford]] <br /> [[College of the Resurrection]]\n}}\n'''Peter George Allan''' {{post-nominals|post-noms=[[Community of the Resurrection|CR]]}} (born 1950) is a British [[Anglican]] priest and [[monk]]. From 2011 to 2019, he was [[Principal (academia)|principal]] of the [[College of the Resurrection]], an [[Anglo-Catholic]] [[theological college]] in [[Mirfield]], West Yorkshire, England. He has been a monk of the [[Community of the Resurrection]] since 1985.\n\n==Early life and education==\nAllan was born in 1950.<ref name=\"Crockford\">{{Crockford| surname = Allan | forenames = Peter George | id = 31730 | accessed = 30 November 2016}}</ref> He studied music at [[Wadham College, Oxford]], graduating with a Bachelor of Arts (BA) degree in 1972:<ref name=\"Crockford\" /><ref name=\"bio - college\" /> as per tradition, his BA was promoted to a Master of Arts (MA Oxon) degree in 1976.<ref name=\"Crockford\" /> In 1972, he [[matriculated]] into the [[College of the Resurrection, Mirfield]], to study theology and train for [[ordination]].<ref name=\"Crockford\" /><ref name=\"bio - college\" /> He left the college after three years to be ordained in the [[Church of England]].<ref name=\"Crockford\" />\n\n==Ordained ministry==\nAllan was [[ordained]] in the Church of England as a [[Deacon#Anglicanism|deacon]] in 1975 and as a [[Priest#Anglican or Episcopalian|priest]] in 1976.<ref name=\"Crockford\" /> From 1975 to 1978, he served his [[curacy]] at St Andrew's Church, [[Stevenage]], an [[Anglo-Catholic]] parish in the [[Diocese of St Albans]].<ref name=\"Crockford\" /><ref>{{cite web|title=Home Page|url=http://stevenagechurch.org/|website= St Andrew and St George's Church, Stevenage|accessdate=30 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=THE PARISH CHURCH OF ST ANDREW & ST GEORGE, STEVENAGE|url=http://stevenagechurch.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/List-of-Rectors-and-Curates.pdf|website=Stevenage Church |accessdate=30 November 2016|format=pdf|year=2015}}</ref> Then, from 1978 to 1982, he was chaplain of [[Wadham College, Oxford]], and a curate of the [[University Church of St Mary the Virgin]], [[Oxford]].<ref name=\"Crockford\" /><ref name=\"bio - college\">{{cite web|title=People: Fr Peter Allan CR|url=http://college.mirfield.org.uk/about-us/people/|website= The College of the Resurrection|accessdate=30 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 1982, Allan joined the [[Community of the Resurrection]] as a [[Novitiate|novice]].<ref name=\"bio - college\" /><ref name=\"study day\">{{cite web|title=Singing Our Faith study day|url=http://www.mirfieldcompanions.org.uk/cd16fl01.pdf|website= Community of the Resurrection|accessdate=30 November 2016|format=pdf|date=July 2016}}</ref> In 1985, he made his [[Religious vows|vows]], thereby becoming a [[monk]] and a full member of the Community of the Resurrection.<ref name=\"Crockford\" /> Since 1985, he has been the [[precentor]] of the community.<ref name=\"study day\" /> In 2011, he was also appointed [[Principal (academia)|principal]] of the [[College of the Resurrection]], an Anglo-Catholic [[theological college]] that is associated with the Community of the Resurrection.<ref name=\"Crockford\" /><ref name=\"bio - college\" /> He is also a lecturer in [[moral theology]] and [[liturgical music]] at the college.<ref name=\"bio - college\" /> He will step down as principal at the end of the 2018/2019 academic year and is the be succeeded by [[Mark Sowerby]], currently Bishop of Horsham.<ref name=\"Sowerby\">{{cite web |title=Bishop of Horsham to be Principal of the College of the Resurrection |url=https://www.chichester.anglican.org/news/2019/04/30/bishop-horsham-be-principal-college-resurrection/ |website=Diocese of Chichester |accessdate=14 May 2019 |language=en |date=30 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Views===\nIn January 2016, Allan signed an [[open letter]] addressed to the Archbishops of Canterbury and York, asking for \"Acknowledgement that we, the Church, have failed in our duty of care to [[LGBTI]] members of the Body of Christ around the world\" and calling for \"Repentance for accepting and promoting discrimination on the grounds of sexuality, and for the pain and rejection that this has caused.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Gay Anglicans and the Primates' Meeting|url=http://www.pcnbritain.org.uk/news/post/gay_anglicans_and_the_primates_meeting|website= Progressive Christianity Network Britain|accessdate=30 November 2016|date=11 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Selected works==\n* {{cite book |editor=Peter Allan |display-editors=et al |title=An English kyriale: music for the Eucharist |date=1991 |publisher=Harper Collins |location=London |isbn=978-0005992692}}\n* {{cite book |editor=Peter Allan |display-editors=et al |title=The Fire and the Clay: The Priest in Today's Church |date=1993 |publisher=SPCK |location=London |isbn=978-0281047154}}\n* {{cite book |editor=George Guiver |editor2= Peter Allan |display-editors=et al |title=Priests in a People's Church |date=2001 |publisher=SPCK |location=London |isbn=978-0281054053}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Allan, Peter}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century Anglican priests]]\n[[Category:21st-century Anglican priests]]\n[[Category:Church of England priests]]\n[[Category:British Anglo-Catholics]]\n[[Category:Anglican monks]]\n[[Category:Fellows of Wadham College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Wadham College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the College of the Resurrection]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British Anglican vicar and monk|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Infobox Christian leader\n| type             = Priest\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Reverend]] Fr\n| name             = Peter Allan\n| honorific-suffix = [[Community of the Resurrection|CR]]\n| title            = [[Principal (academia)|Principal]] of the [[College of the Resurrection]]\n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| church           = [[Church of England]]\n| province         = \n| diocese          = [[Anglican Diocese of Leeds|Leeds]]\n| term             = 2011\u20132019\n| predecessor      = [[Joseph Kennedy (priest)|Joseph Kennedy]]\n| successor        = [[Mark Sowerby]]\n| other_post       = Monk of the [[Community of the Resurrection]] (1985\u2013present)\n<!---------- Orders ---------->\n| ordination       = 1975 (deacon) <br /> 1976 (priest)\n| ordained_by      = \n| consecration     = \n| consecrated_by   = \n<!---------- Personal details ---------->\n| birth_name       = \n| birth_date       = {{birth year and age|1950}} <!-- {{Birth date|df=y|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| birth_place      = <!-- City, administrative region, sovereign state (per [[Template:Infobox person]]) -->\n| death_date       = <!-- {{Death date and age|df=y|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place      = <!-- as birth_place -->\n| buried           = <!-- or | tomb = -->\n| resting_place_co-ordinates = \n| nationality      = British\n| religion         = [[Anglicanism]]\n| residence        = \n| parents          = \n| spouse           = \n| children         = \n| occupation       = \n| profession       = <!-- or | previous_post = -->\n| education        =\n| alma_mater       = [[Wadham College, Oxford]] <br /> [[College of the Resurrection]]\n}}\n'''Peter George Allan''' {{post-nominals|post-noms=[[Community of the Resurrection|CR]]}} (born 1950) is a British [[Anglican]] priest and [[monk]]. From 2011 to 2019, he was [[Principal (academia)|principal]] of the [[College of the Resurrection]], an [[Anglo-Catholic]] [[theological college]] in [[Mirfield]], West Yorkshire, England. He has been a monk of the [[Community of the Resurrection]] since 1985.\n\n==Early life and education==\nAllan was born in 1950.<ref name=\"Crockford\">{{Crockford| surname = Allan | forenames = Peter George | id = 31730 | accessed = 30 November 2016}}</ref> He studied music at [[Wadham College, Oxford]], graduating with a Bachelor of Arts (BA) degree in 1972:<ref name=\"Crockford\" /><ref name=\"bio - college\" /> as per tradition, his BA was promoted to a Master of Arts (MA Oxon) degree in 1976.<ref name=\"Crockford\" /> In 1972, he [[matriculated]] into the [[College of the Resurrection, Mirfield]], to study theology and train for [[ordination]].<ref name=\"Crockford\" /><ref name=\"bio - college\" /> He left the college after three years to be ordained in the [[Church of England]].<ref name=\"Crockford\" />\n\n==Ordained ministry==\nAllan was [[ordained]] in the Church of England as a [[Deacon#Anglicanism|deacon]] in 1975 and as a [[Priest#Anglican or Episcopalian|priest]] in 1976.<ref name=\"Crockford\" /> From 1975 to 1978, he served his [[curacy]] at St Andrew's Church, [[Stevenage]], an [[Anglo-Catholic]] parish in the [[Diocese of St Albans]].<ref name=\"Crockford\" /><ref>{{cite web|title=Home Page|url=http://stevenagechurch.org/|website= St Andrew and St George's Church, Stevenage|accessdate=30 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=THE PARISH CHURCH OF ST ANDREW & ST GEORGE, STEVENAGE|url=http://stevenagechurch.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/List-of-Rectors-and-Curates.pdf|website=Stevenage Church |accessdate=30 November 2016|format=pdf|year=2015}}</ref> Then, from 1978 to 1982, he was chaplain of [[Wadham College, Oxford]], and a curate of the [[University Church of St Mary the Virgin]], [[Oxford]].<ref name=\"Crockford\" /><ref name=\"bio - college\">{{cite web|title=People: Fr Peter Allan CR|url=http://college.mirfield.org.uk/about-us/people/|website= The College of the Resurrection|accessdate=30 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 1982, Allan joined the [[Community of the Resurrection]] as a [[Novitiate|novice]].<ref name=\"bio - college\" /><ref name=\"study day\">{{cite web|title=Singing Our Faith study day|url=http://www.mirfieldcompanions.org.uk/cd16fl01.pdf|website= Community of the Resurrection|accessdate=30 November 2016|format=pdf|date=July 2016}}</ref> In 1985, he made his [[Religious vows|vows]], thereby becoming a [[monk]] and a full member of the Community of the Resurrection.<ref name=\"Crockford\" /> Since 1985, he has been the [[precentor]] of the community.<ref name=\"study day\" /> In 2011, he was also appointed [[Principal (academia)|principal]] of the [[College of the Resurrection]], an Anglo-Catholic [[theological college]] that is associated with the Community of the Resurrection.<ref name=\"Crockford\" /><ref name=\"bio - college\" /> He is also a lecturer in [[moral theology]] and [[liturgical music]] at the college.<ref name=\"bio - college\" /> He will step down as principal at the end of the 2018/2019 academic year and is the be succeeded by [[Mark Sowerby]], currently Bishop of Horsham.<ref name=\"Sowerby\">{{cite web |title=Bishop of Horsham to be Principal of the College of the Resurrection |url=https://www.chichester.anglican.org/news/2019/04/30/bishop-horsham-be-principal-college-resurrection/ |website=Diocese of Chichester |accessdate=14 May 2019 |language=en |date=30 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Views===\nIn January 2016, Allan signed an [[open letter]] addressed to the Archbishops of Canterbury and York, asking for \"Acknowledgement that we, the Church, have failed in our duty of care to [[LGBTI]] members of the Body of Christ around the world\" and calling for \"Repentance for accepting and promoting discrimination on the grounds of sexuality, and for the pain and rejection that this has caused.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Gay Anglicans and the Primates' Meeting|url=http://www.pcnbritain.org.uk/news/post/gay_anglicans_and_the_primates_meeting|website= Progressive Christianity Network Britain|accessdate=30 November 2016|date=11 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Selected works==\n* {{cite book |editor=Peter Allan |display-editors=et al |title=An English kyriale: music for the Eucharist |date=1991 |publisher=Harper Collins |location=London |isbn=978-0005992692}}\n* {{cite book |editor=Peter Allan |display-editors=et al |title=The Fire and the Clay: The Priest in Today's Church |date=1993 |publisher=SPCK |location=London |isbn=978-0281047154}}\n* {{cite book |editor=George Guiver |editor2= Peter Allan |display-editors=et al |title=Priests in a People's Church |date=2001 |publisher=SPCK |location=London |isbn=978-0281054053}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Allan, Peter}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century Anglican priests]]\n[[Category:21st-century Anglican priests]]\n[[Category:Church of England priests]]\n[[Category:British Anglo-Catholics]]\n[[Category:Anglican monks]]\n[[Category:Fellows of Wadham College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Wadham College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the College of the Resurrection]]\n", "name_user": "Dodgerjammy", "label": "safe", "comment": "Not a vicar as not instituted to a benefice.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peter_Allan_(priest)"}
{"title_page": "Iron Chef America", "text_new": "{{short description|Competitive cooking show based on the Japanese original}}\n{{more citations needed|date=November 2007}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = Iron Chef America\n| image                = Iron Chef America foodn logo.png\n| caption              = \n| show_name_2          = '''Iron Chef America: The Series'''\n| genre                = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Reality television]]\n* [[Cooking show]]\n}}\n| director             = \n| creative_director    = \n| presenter            = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Alton Brown]]\n* [[Kevin Brauch]]\n* [[Mark Dacascos]]\n* [[Jet Tila]]\n}}\n| starring             = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Mario Batali]] <small>(retired)</small>\n* [[Bobby Flay]] <small>(retired)</small>\n* [[Wolfgang Puck]] <small>(retired)</small>\n* [[Masaharu Morimoto]]\n* [[Cat Cora]] <small>(retired)</small>\n* [[Michael Symon]]\n* [[Jose Garces]]\n* [[Marc Forgione]]\n* [[Geoffrey Zakarian]]\n* [[Alexandra Guarnaschelli|Alex Guarnaschelli]]\n* [[Stephanie Izard]]\n}}\n| country              = United States\n| language             = English\n| num_seasons          = 13\n| num_episodes         = 205\n| list_episodes        = List of Iron Chef America episodes\n| executive_producer   = Stu Schreiberg\n| producer             = John Bravakis<br />Steve Kroopnick\n| supervising_producer = \n| asst_producer        = \n| composer             = Craig Marks\n| editor               = Morgen Kassel\n| location             = Los Angeles, California<br />New York City\n| cinematography       =\n| camera               = [[Multiple-camera setup|Multi-camera]]\n| runtime              = 46 minutes\n| network              = [[Food Network]]\n| picture_format       = [[480i]] ([[Standard-definition television|SDTV]])<br>(2005-2008)<br>[[1080i]] ([[High-definition television|HDTV]])<br>(2008-2018)\n| audio_format         = \n| first_aired          = {{Start date|2005|3|6}}\n| last_aired           = July 22, 2018\n| related              = ''[[Iron Chef]]''<br />''[[Iron Chef UK]]''<br />''[[The Next Iron Chef]]''<br />''[[Iron Chef Gauntlet]]''<br />''[[Iron Chef Showdown]]''<br />\n| website              = http://www.foodnetwork.com/iron-chef-america/index.html\n}}\n'''''Iron Chef America''''' is an American [[cooking show]] based on [[Fuji Television]]'s ''[[Iron Chef]]'', and is the second American adaptation of the series, following the failed ''Iron Chef USA'' that aired in 2001.  The show is produced by [[Food Network]], which also carried a dubbed version of the original ''Iron Chef''.  Like the original Japanese program, the program is a culinary game show. In each episode, a new challenger chef competes against one of the resident \"Iron Chefs\" in a one-hour cooking competition based on a secret ingredient or ingredients, and sometimes theme.\n\nThe show is presented as a successor to the original ''Iron Chef'', as opposed to being a remake.  The Chairman is portrayed by actor and [[martial artist]] [[Mark Dacascos]], who is introduced as the nephew of the original Japanese chairman [[Takeshi Kaga]].  The commentary is provided solely by [[Alton Brown]] and [[Kevin Brauch]] is the floor reporter.  The music is written by composer Craig Marks, who released the soundtrack titled \"Iron Chef America & The Next Iron Chef\" by the end of 2010. In addition, regular ICA judge and ''[[Chopped (TV series)|Chopped]]'' host [[Ted Allen]] provided additional floor commentary for two special battles: Battle First Thanksgiving (Symon/Flay v. Cora/Morimoto) and Battle White House Produce (Batali/Lagasse v. Flay/Comerford).\n\nPer the introduction fiction from the ''Battle of the Masters'' miniseries (and ignoring story elements from the 2002 ''Iron Chef'' Japan Cup Special), Chairman Kaga (the character) has ordered his nephew to continue the tradition of [[Kitchen Stadium]], initially in Los Angeles, where the ''Battle of the Master''s took place, before establishing a permanent Kitchen Stadium in New York's [[Chelsea Market]].  For the ''Battle of the Masters'', the elder Chairman dispatched two Iron Chefs: [[Hiroyuki Sakai]] and [[Masaharu Morimoto]]. In Season 11, the show's fiction expanded to include international Iron Chefs, spread by the Chairman \"like [[Johnny Appleseed]]\". In the first episode of that season, ''[[Iron Chef UK]]'' chef [[Judy Joo]] competed on the US show against Iron Chef Guarnaschelli as an Iron Chef.\n\nUnlike the original ''Iron Chef'' or ''Iron Chef USA'', Alton Brown, rather than the Chairman, is credited as the show's host.\n\nIn 2017, ''[[Iron Chef Showdown]]'' premiered as the spiritual successor to ''Iron Chef America'', with a revised format and returning Iron Chefs Bobby Flay, Jose Garces, Alex Guarnaschelli, and Michael Symon joined by ''[[Iron Chef Gauntlet]]'' winner [[Stephanie Izard]]. On April 5, 2018, Food Network announced ''Iron Chef America'' returning under its original name, with [[Jet Tila]] serving as floor reporter.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/iron-chef-america-returns-to-food-network-with-classic-fan-favorite-format-300625155.html|title=\"Iron Chef America\" returns To Food Network With Classic Fan-favorite Format|website=[[PR Newswire]]|date=April 5, 2018|accessdate=April 6, 2018}}</ref> Notably, Iron Chef Bobby Flay will not be returning, as he dramatically announced his exit from ''Iron Chef'' during his last battle on ''Showdown''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://pagesix.com/2018/02/26/bobby-flay-thought-quitting-iron-chef-on-air-would-be-good-tv/ |title=Bobby Flay thought quitting 'Iron Chef' on air \u2018would be good TV\u2019 |accessdate=2018-04-05 |first=Jessica |last=Sager |date=2018-02-26}}</ref>\n\n==The Iron Chefs==\nOn this version of ''Iron Chef'', the Iron Chefs have either been previous Food Network personalities, are current personalities, were part of the original ''Iron Chef'', or earned their position on ''[[The Next Iron Chef]].''<ref name=\"FortuneArticle\">{{cite web |url=http://money.cnn.com/2007/11/21/smbusiness/Ironchef.fsb/index.htm?section=money_latest |title=Michael Symon back in action: The Lola chef wins his first Iron Chef competition against Ricky Moore |accessdate=2007-11-22 |first=Joanne |last=Chen |date=2007-11-21 |work=Fortune Small Business |publisher=CNN Money}}</ref>\n\nThe winning percentage for Iron Chefs participating on Iron Chef America is an average. The win/loss data is based solely on the performance of the participant as an Iron Chef in ''Iron Chef America: The Series'' and the ''Battle of the Masters'' but does not include the results from ''Iron Chef Showdown''.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" align=\"left\" style=\"margin: auto; text-align: center;\"\n! Iron Chef\n! Seasons\n! Specialty\n! Win\n! Loss\n! Draw\n! Total\n! Win %{{ref|101}}\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | Mario Batali <small>(retired)</small>\n| align=\"left\" | BOM, 1 - 6\n| align=\"left\" | Italian\n| 19\n| 5\n| 0\n| 24\n| 79.2%\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | Cat Cora <small>(retired)</small>\n| align=\"left\" | 1 - 10\n| align=\"left\" | Greek/Mediterranean\n| 21\n| 12\n| 1\n| 34\n| 63.2%\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | Bobby Flay{{ref|102}} <small>(retired)</small>\n| align=\"left\" |BOM, 1 - 12\n| align=\"left\" | Southwestern\n| 43\n| 16\n| 2\n| 61\n| 72.1%\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | Marc Forgione{{ref|103}}\n| align=\"left\" |9 -\n| align=\"left\" | Modern American\n| 8\n| 7\n| 0\n| 15\n| 53.0%\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | Jose Garces{{ref|104}}\n| align=\"left\" |8 -\n| align=\"left\" | Latin Fusion\n| 16\n| 7\n| 0\n| 23\n| 69.6%\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | Alex Guarnaschelli{{ref|105}}\n| align=\"left\" |11 -\n| align=\"left\" | Modern American <!--Do not change to French; she was trained partially in France; specialization per FN bio--> <!--Bio nowhere states \"American market garden\" - please see FN Bio before reverting.-->\n| 7\n| 4\n| 0\n| 11\n| 63.6%\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | Stephanie Izard {{ref|109}}\n| align=\"left